ift for WASP-18 b,\nfinding that T_shift=356 seconds after 10 years for Q'*=10^6, which is much\nlarger than the estimated 28 seconds quoted in WASP-18 b discovery paper. We\nattempted to constrain Q'* via a study of the entire population of known\ntransiting hot Jupiters, but our results were inconclusive, requiring a more\ndetailed treatment of transit survey sensitivities at long periods. We conclude\nthat the most informative and straight-forward constraints on Q'* will be\nobtained by direct observational measurements of the shift in transit arrival\ntimes in individual hot Jupiter systems. We show that this is achievable across\nthe mass spectrum of exoplanet host stars within a decade, and will directly\nprobe the effects of stellar interior structure on tidal dissipation.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 21 Feb 2014 21:00:15 GMT"}],"update_date":"2015-06-18"}
